      "record": "32-36-14",
      "detail": "8th in Atlantic Division",
      "live_strip": null,
      "lotl": {
        "label": "What's Going On With the Leafs",
        "body": "The Maple Leafs' season ended not with a bang but a whimper - a seven-game losing streak that turned the final weeks into an autopsy. <strong>Toronto finished 32-36-14, thirty-one games behind the Atlantic Division leaders, their 78 points good enough for eighth place and a 15th playoff seed that doesn't exist.</strong> This wasn't a collapse; it was a slow-motion failure, a team that never quite found its footing and paid for it when March and April arrived.\n\nThe rebuild conversation starts now. Brendan Shanahan and the front office face hard questions about roster construction, goaltending depth, and whether the current core can coexist. The draft lottery looms - Toronto needs lottery luck or a trade-deadline move to reset. <strong>Watch for coaching stability and free-agent targets this summer; the Leafs can't afford another season of drift.</strong> The Atlantic is brutal, and patience is wearing thin in a market that demands playoffs, not moral victories. The foundation exists. The execution never did.",
        "updated": "Updated April 19, 2026"
      },
